column37: Percentage of linguistically-isolated households by Community Plan Area. Linguistic isolation describes individuals who have difficulty speaking English, and their lack of English or limited English may isolate them from other segments of the population.
column40: The Hardship Index compares the 2010 economic conditions of one Community Plan Area to another. Based on a methodology developed by the Nelson A. Rockefeller Institute of Government, the Index standardizes U.S. Census Bureau demographic and socio-economic variables, including unemployment, age dependency, education, income level, crowded housing, and poverty, and then averages them together, yielding a score on a scale of 0-100.
column43: Per capita income is the total income divided by the total population, and the data is summarized by Community Plan Area.
column46: Percentage of residents age 16 and over who are actively looking for employment and are unable to find a job by Community Plan Area. This does not include workers who have stopped seeking employment.
column49: The total population below the Federal Poverty Level (FPL) in 2010. The FPL for a family of four was $22,050 in 2010.
column52: Percentage of the population below the Federal Poverty Level (FPL) in 2010. The FPL for a family of four was $22,050 in 2010.
column55: Population that is below 200% of the Federal Poverty Level (FPL) in 2010. Two hundred percent of the FPL for a family of four was $44,100 in 2010.
column58: Percentage of the population that is below 200% of the Federal Poverty Level (FPL) in 2010. Two hundred percent of the FPL for a family of four was $44,100 in 2010.
column61: Number of residents living in census tracts with poverty rates greater than 40% by Community Plan Area.
column64: Proportion of residents age 25 and over within a Community Plan Area that did not graduate from high school.
column67: Proportion of residents age 25 and over within a Community Plan Area that graduated from high school.
column70: Percentage of residents age 25 and over with a Bachelor?s degree or higher by Community Plan Area.
column73: Life expectancy at birth in years by Public Use Microdata Area (PUMA). Life expectancy at birth was calculated with mortality data from the California Department of Public Health, Center for Health Statistics, and population estimates from the U.S. Census Bureau.
column82: Percentage of adults ever diagnosed with diabetes by Health District .
column85: Age-adjusted rate of coronary heart disease mortality per 100,000 residents by City Council District. Mortality data is from Los Angeles County mortality records. The ICD-10 codes of coronary heart disease are I11 and I20-I25.
column88: Heart attacks include hospitalizations with a principal diagnosis using ICD-9 code 410 (includes cardiac infarction; coronary embolism, occlusion, rupture, or thrombosis; infarction of the heart, myocardium, or ventricle; rupture of the heart, myocardium or ventricle) in adults age 45 and over by zip code.
column91: Age-adjusted heart attack rates per 10,000 include hospitalizations with a principal diagnosis using ICD-9 code 410 (includes cardiac infarction; coronary embolism, occlusion, rupture, or thrombosis; infarction of the heart, myocardium, or ventricle; rupture of the heart, myocardium or ventricle) in adults age 45 and over by zip code.
column94: Age-adjusted rate of stroke mortality per 100,000 residents by City Council District. Mortality data is from Los Angeles County mortality records. The primary ICD-10 codes for stroke are I60-I69.
column97: Age-adjusted rate of diabetes mortality per 100,000 by City Council District. Mortality data is from Los Angeles County mortality records. The ICD-10 codes for diabetes are E10-E14.
column100: Crude rate of respiratory disease mortality per 100,000 by Community Plan Area. Mortality data is from Los Angeles County mortality records. Diseases of the respiratory system include all deaths classified by the ICD-10 diagnoses code J.
column103: Asthma emergency department visits include visits with a principal diagnosis using ICD-9 code 493 in children age 17 and under by zip code.
column106: Asthma rates include emergency department visits with a principal diagnosis using ICD-9 code 493 in children age 17 and under by zip code.

column124: Asthma rates include hospitalizations with a principal diagnosis using ICD-9 code 493 in children age 18 and over by zip code.
column127: Percent of adults (18+ years old) who reported fair or poor health by Health District.
column130: Percent of children (age 17 and under) who reported fair or poor health by Health District.
column133: Average number of unhealthy days due to poor physical and/or mental health during the past 30 days for adults (18+ years old) by Health District.
column136: Average number of days limited due to poor physical and/or mental health during the past 30 days for adults (18+ years old) by Health District.
column139: Percentage of adults who received sufficient social and emotional support by Health District.
column142: Percentage of adults with depression by Health District.
column145: Prevalence of overweight adults by Health District. The term overweight describes a weight range that is above what is medically accepted as healthy. The most common measure of healthy and unhealthy weight is the Body Mass Index (BMI), which is a function that takes into account both height and weight. Overweight individuals have a BMI of 25.0 to 29.9.
column148: Prevalence of obese adults by Health District. The term obese describes a weight range that is above what is medically accepted as healthy. The most common measure of healthy and unhealthy weight is the Body Mass Index (BMI), which is a function that takes into account both height and weight. Obesity is defined as having a BMI above 30.
column151: Prevalence of childhood obesity by Community Plan Area. Obesity is defined as a BMI at or above the 95th percentile for children of the same sex and age.
column154: Percentage of adults who met physical activity guidelines for aerobic and muscle-strengthening activity each week by Health District. According to the 2008 Physical Activity Guidelines for Americans, adults should participate in at least 150 minutes a week of moderate intensity physical activity, or 75 minutes a week of vigorous-intensity aerobic physical activity. While no specific amount of time is recommended for muscle-strengthening exercise, the guidelines suggest adults should engage in muscle-strengthening activities two days a week.
column157: Percentage of children who participated in physical activity per week by Health District. Children and adolescents should engage in 60 minutes or more of physical activity daily, and muscle-strengthening and bone-strengthening physical activity on at least 3 days of the week.
column160: Percentage of low birth weight infants by zip code. Infants are considered low birth weight if they weigh less than 2,500 grams (or 5.51 pounds).
column163: Health Professional Shortage Areas (HPSAs) lack a sufficient number of primary care, dental, and mental health professionals. HPSA is a federal designation that applies to areas with unmet health care needs. This designation is based on a ratio of population to health professionals and access to healthcare. This indicator shows the number of people living in a Primary Care HPSA by Community Plan Area.
column166: Walkability is a measure of the pedestrian environment within each Community Plan Area. The Walkability Index is based on a number of factors that influence whether a person will walk, including land use diversity, residential density, retail density, and intersection density. Higher scores represent more walkable areas.
column169: Intersections per square mile for each Community Plan Area.
column172: A composite score for land use mix within each Community Plan Area. The index assesses six different uses: single family residential, multifamily residential, retail, entertainment, office, and institutional or community-serving. Values were normalized between 0 and 1, with 1 representing an even distribution of the 6 uses.
column175: Number of diverse uses within each Community Plan Area. The list of diverse uses was derived from the LEED for Neighborhood Development Checklist. The list includes 19 uses separated into four categories: food retail, community-serving retail, services, civic and community facilities.

column181: Multifamily residential area by Community Plan Area.

column187: Office area by Community Plan Area.

column196: Acres of parks per 1,000 residents for each Community Plan Area. This includes city and county parks, state parks, and federal parks, but it does not include features such as cemeteries, golf courses, amusement parks, or senior centers.
column199: Percentage of population within one-half mile of a park or open space by Community Plan Area. Distances are calculated based on the street network.

column274: Rate of CalFresh vendors per 1,000 households participating in CalFresh by Community Plan Area.
